    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-rh-index-comparison-primary",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary relative hemolysis index validation against FDA pump experimental data",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-hemolysis-experimental-reference",
      "description": "This validation result captures the comprehensive comparison of CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RH) values against published experimental measurements for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump across all five flow-speed operating points (2.5 L/min at 2500 RPM, 3.5 L/min at 3000 RPM, 4.5 L/min at 3500 RPM, 5.0 L/min at 3500 RPM, and 6.0 L/min at 4000 RPM). The simulation campaign was executed using ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 with the Lagrangian particle-tracking hemolysis model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law correlation). Mesh independence was confirmed at 4.2 million polyhedral cells, with GCI values below 3.1% for all QoIs. Turbulence was modeled using the SST k-omega formulation with y+ maintained between 1 and 5 on all blood-contacting surfaces. Predicted RH values ranged from 0.71 to 0.94 across the five operating points, with a mean absolute relative error of 8.3% against the experimental reference dataset. All five operating points satisfied the RH < 1 acceptance criterion. The simulation team conducted a dedicated sensitivity study varying the hemolysis model exponent (alpha = 0.765 ± 0.05) and confirmed that RH predictions remained below 1.0 across the full parameter range, providing additional confidence in the robustness of the validation outcome. Blood rheology was modeled as a non-Newtonian fluid using the Carreau model with parameters fit to the experimental viscometry data supplied with the FDA benchmark dataset. Inlet boundary conditions were specified as fully developed velocity profiles derived from phase-contrast MRI measurements. This result constitutes the primary evidence supporting the credibility claim that the CFD model is adequate for identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions within the defined COU.",
      "outcomeValue": "RH_mean=0.83; max_RH=0.94; MARE=8.3%; all 5 operating points satisfy RH<1",
